<div id='communityQuestionsWithAnswers'>
<div class='communityQuestionAndAnswer'>
<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<a href="/questions/708951-why-does-lord-caversham-calls-his-son">Why does Lord Caversham calls his son, Lord Goring, (sir)?! 
It got me confused, is it a cultural thing?! or people used to call their sons that in the past?!</a>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_708951'><a id="like_count_community_question_708951" rel="nofollow" href="/rating/voters/708951?resource_type=CommunityQuestion"><span class="likesCount">5 likes</span></a>&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;<a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F5296.An_Ideal_Husband">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/708951-why-does-lord-caversham-calls-his-son">5 years ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/708951-why-does-lord-caversham-calls-his-son">See all 2 answers</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/9348576-monique"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1604146548i/9348576._UX100_CR0,28,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/9348576-monique">Monique</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">It&apos;s also part of the humor. Lord Caversham calling his son that shows his indignation and disapproval on what his son is (or is not) doing (by not re<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">It's also part of the humor. Lord Caversham calling his son that shows his indignation and disapproval on what his son is (or is not) doing (by not referring to him as his son, or in some familiar, loving way was they usually did then). When Lord Goring replies back to his father with "Lord Caversham" it reaffirms their "strained" relationship, and besides, it's funny. <a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerFooter'>

